# Modularity and class split rule (`src/`)

Refactors in this project must prioritize low coupling and small, understandable modules.

## Class/file constraint

- **One top-level class per file** for new code and for files touched during refactor.
- If a file grows and contains multiple top-level classes, split into focused modules (`foo_service.py`, `foo_parser.py`, etc.).
- Keep class names and filenames aligned so ownership is obvious.

## Module boundaries

- Keep orchestration, parsing, graph modeling, and web concerns in separate modules.
- Move reusable logic into functions/helpers rather than adding more responsibilities to an existing class.
- Prefer dependency injection (arguments/protocols) over importing sibling concrete classes directly.

## Exceptions

- Pure function modules (no class) are allowed.
- `__init__.py` files can re-export symbols and do not need classes.
- Small dataclass/value-object modules are fine as single-class files.

## Anti-patterns

- Avoid "god files" that collect multiple classes for convenience.
- Avoid adding a second class to an existing class file unless explicitly requested by the user.
- Avoid mixing unrelated responsibilities in one class just to keep code local.
